      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i keep seeing memory usage climbing in our testing environment for this small C++ module. pretty sure there's a leak in how we're handling the order objects. can u look at this snippet and tell me why it isnt deallocating properly?\n\nvoid process_orders(Order* orders, int count) {\n    for (int i = 0; i < count; ++i) {\n        Order* current = new Order(orders[i].id);\n        // ... some logic here ...\n        if (orders[i].status == CANCELLED) {\n            continue;\n        }\n        // we forgot to delete 'current' in some paths\n    }\n}\n\nhow do i fix this using smart pointers so i dont have to manually manage the memory every time?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The memory usage is climbing because the order objects are being created with `new` but never given a `delete` (or `delete[]`) when the loop finishes, and the `continue` statement skips the cleanup for cancelled orders, leaving them orphaned in the heap. It's like a shopkeeper buying a stack of boxes, but forgetting to put them back in the warehouse when they're cancelled, so they pile up forever.\n\nTo fix this using smart pointers, you simply replace the raw `new` and `delete` with `std::unique_ptr<Order>`. The compiler will handle the allocation and deallocation for you, ensuring that every single object is freed exactly once, even if the loop skips some.\n\nHere is the corrected version:\n\n```cpp\n#include <memory>\n\nvoid process_orders(std::unique_ptr<Order[]> orders, int count) {\n    for (int i = 0; i < count; ++i) {\n        // Create a unique_ptr that owns the Order object\n        std::unique_ptr<Order> current = std::make_unique<Order>(orders[i].id);\n        \n        // ... some logic here ...\n        \n        if (orders[i].status == CANCELLED)",
