      "content": "thanks for that. the unique_ptr approach makes sense. but wait, i noticed you used `std::unique_ptr<Order[]> orders` in the function signature in your example. shouldn't that be handled differently if the input array is managed elsewhere? \n\nand also, in a high-frequency trading context, i'm worried about the overhead of constant allocations. is there a way to use something like an object pool or just more efficient smart pointer usage to stop these \"orphaned\" objects from cluttering the heap?",
      "source": "evaluator"
