    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you've hit the nail on the head! That's a classic pitfall in C++ memory management. If you pass a raw array `Order* orders` into your function, you are responsible for managing the lifetime of that entire array. You cannot just magically \"own\" the array inside the function without a `new` or `malloc` call, and if you don't, you're back to square one with manual management.\n\nHowever, in a high-frequency trading (HFT) context, you absolutely do not want to be paying the cost of `new` and `delete` for every single order object. That is exactly why **Object Pools** are your best friend here.\n\nThink of an object pool like a pre-stocked warehouse of boxes. Instead of buying a new box every time you need one (which is slow and expensive), you grab one from the pre-stocked pile. When the box is done, you return it to the pile. This eliminates the allocation overhead entirely.\n\nHere is how you can refactor this to use a pool, which is the \"goblin-adjacent\" solution for HFT:\n\n### The Strategy: A Simple Object Pool\n\nWe create a small helper class that",
